  1. Plot lifespan (MaxLongevity_m) versus female body mass (Body mass female mean).
#Plot lifespan v body mass
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(d$Body_mass_female_mean, d$MaxLongevity_m)
plot(log(d$Body_mass_female_mean), d$MaxLongevity_m)
plot(log(d$Body_mass_female_mean), log(d$MaxLongevity_m))

Question Is the relationship linear? - The relationship of the last two plots do appear to be linear, while the first plot does not show a linear relationship.

  1. Run linear models of lifespan ~ female body mass, lifespan ~ log(female body mass), and log(lifespan) ~ log(female body mass).
#Create the models
ls_m1 <- lm(data = d, MaxLongevity_m ~ Body_mass_female_mean)
ls_m2 <- lm(data = d, MaxLongevity_m ~ log(Body_mass_female_mean))
ls_m3 <- lm(data = d, log(MaxLongevity_m) ~ log(Body_mass_female_mean))

  1. Generate the QQ plots for all three linear models.

Question Do they appear to be normally distributed? - Yes, as they more or less fall on or near the linear line.

  1. Run a Shapiro-Wilk test on residuals for all three models.

s2 <- shapiro.test(ls_m2$residuals)
s3 <- shapiro.test(ls_m3$residuals)
